message:
fix(rchd/benchmark_queue): make rate-limit check+insert atomic under one Mutex acquisition

`BenchmarkQueue::enqueue` gates per-worker enqueues by a min_interval
rate limit. The rate-limit read and the timestamp insert were issued
inside *separate* `self.last_triggered.lock()` acquisitions:

```
{
    let last = self.last_triggered.lock().expect(...);
    if let Some(last_at) = last.get(&worker_id) {
        if since < self.min_interval { return Err(RateLimit); }
    }
}

{
    let mut last = self.last_triggered.lock().expect(...);
    last.insert(worker_id.clone(), now);
}
```

Two concurrent callers for the same worker could both pass the "not
too recent" predicate inside their respective first locks (no write
has happened yet) and then both arrive at the second lock to insert.
Both enqueue requests succeed, violating the per-worker interval — the
exact invariant the rate limit exists to enforce.

Fix: collapse both critical sections into one `lock()` that holds the
MutexGuard through read and write. `last` goes from `let last = ...`
to `let mut last = ...` so the same guard can `.get(...)` and then
`.insert(...)`. The guard is released at the end of the combined
block, same as before, so there is no additional contention during the
downstream enqueue work.

Regression test added: `test_concurrent_enqueue_respects_rate_limit`
spawns 16 threads that all try to enqueue for the same worker within
microseconds. With a 60-second min_interval, exactly one must succeed.
Before the fix this test observes multiple successes intermittently;
after the fix it deterministically passes.

Fixes the check-then-act race that made per-worker benchmark rate
limits advisory rather than binding under concurrent load.

